An unprecedented future
JERUSALEM – With my nearly 90 years of life, I cannot recall a time when the past was so insignificant for political decision-making.
None of the significant developments of the present was predicted by anyone.
Experts did examine the past, but because of their incarceration within old paradigms, they were unable to derive the future from it.
Due to the dynamic complexity of today's world, where events are increasingly interdependent against the backdrop of a scientifically grounded and rapidly evolving global economy, we are unable to predict the future based on a linear extrapolation of the past.
The only certainty is that the future will be determined by scientific progress and innovation, which cannot be known in advance.
As a result of these developments, the traditional power of states and their leaders is waning. In today's globalized economy, it is not politicians but innovators who exert the greatest influence.
The globalized economy affects all states, yet no single state can determine its outcome because science and technology know no boundaries.
Global operating companies want to pursue their business activities worldwide, which on one hand undermines sovereignty, but on the other hand weakens racism and prejudices as well as significantly reduces nationalism.
Due to this transformation, the fate of this world now rests in the hands of a younger generation. They are more technologically adept than their parents and are connected through social networks that overcome national borders, language barriers, or different forms of government.
The young founders of Facebook and Google exert a greater global influence than many heads of state and generals.
These young people also form the vanguard of emerging political protest movements.
The "Arab Spring," the tent protests in Israel, Occupy Wall Street, and the protests in Russia do not mark a clash of cultures, but rather a generational battle.
The young generation knows that the way states and economies are currently run is inappropriate for the new times.
But there are political "jumpers-on" who want to take advantage of this latest awakening. However, not through the further development of a freedom agenda, but through the introduction of new forms of coercion.
In the Arab world, it is primarily Islamist extremists who take over the protests of the younger generation and steal the revolution from them.
Israel has responded positively to the will of the younger generation, but it should and must not interfere with the events in the Arab world.
We stand with the rebelling boys at heart and their legitimate longing for freedom and fundamental rights, which should enable them to make their voices heard, choose their political leadership, and earn their living.
The Israelis are waiting for the day when their country will no longer be the only democracy in the region, because existing as an island of prosperity amidst a sea of poverty is unnatural.
However, there is a serious concern that politically well-organized extremists will try to win control over less well-organized Liberals during elections, thereby preventing peace and stability.
Radical fundamentalists cannot offer real solutions to the fundamental problems of the region.
The current social upheavals threaten their way of life, which includes the discrimination of women and the prohibition of modern education.
However, only fundamental reforms of entrenched authority can pave the way towards freedom and growth.
Israel can serve as an example when it comes to achieving economic prosperity and social freedom, for its success is founded on the fact that the country had absolutely nothing to start with.
Upon our return home, we were rich in history but lacking in natural resources.
We could only rely on our human capital.
Therefore, we invested in education and science. For this reason, we today have the highest percentage per capita of scientists and patents.
Approximately 95 percent of our agriculture is based on high technology.
We consume less water and yet still achieve higher harvest yields per square meter of cultivation area than any other country in the world.
What Israel achieves, others can also accomplish.
We are happy to offer our help wherever it is desired.
Together and in peace with our neighbors, we can shape a region of hope, development, and success.
Primarily, we must do everything in our power to end the conflict with the Palestinians.
Israel was not created to rule over another people, and that is not part of Israel's destiny.
We are genuinely interested in the creation of a Palestinian state that exists peacefully and side by side with Israel - the democratic state of the Jewish people.
For us, peace is both a moral imperative and a national security strategy, as resolving the conflict would help stabilize the region by neutralizing the extremists who seek to manipulate civil movements in pursuit of their radical agenda.
The international community can support those countries that strive for freedom and progress through incentives.
At the same time, decisive and landmark political measures must be taken against the extremists.
Especially Iran is a source of moral decay, where one promotes extremism and blocks reforms. It crushes legitimate protests of its own citizens and works against the brave Syrians who are currently fighting for their freedom.
Additionally, Iran uses several proxies to foment terrorism against moderate forces in the Palestinian Authority, in Lebanon, and in Iraq.
If Iran manages to acquire nuclear weapons, its leaders could shake the Middle East and Middle East, and stir up even more extremism and violence.
Israel will defend itself if Iran continues to demand the destruction of Israel.
But Israel is not threatened alone. Iran is a danger for peace and stability worldwide.
The democracies of the world have declared that they will not permit Iran to acquire nuclear weapons. It is their duty to follow through on this pledge before it becomes impossible.
Beyond these short-term challenges, we all have the duty to fundamentally change the way we prepare our children for dealing with today's world.
In an era where the past has become irrelevant for predicting the future, education must offer all children the opportunity to realize their potential.
The teachers of today should motivate our children towards creativity and innovation.
Self-realization is just as important as free expression of opinion.
I am writing this article at the age of 88, but not because I have learned from experience.
Contrary to this: experience is overvalued and often restricts the courage that is necessary to face the future and create an unprecedented new world.
The future is already here. Looking back makes no sense.
